{"parse":{"title":"Nigeria gully erosion crisis","pageid":49958243,"revid":843927540,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg/220px-Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"293\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg/330px-Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg/440px-Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3120\" data-file-height=\"4160\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ikot_Effangha_gully_Calabar.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A gully in Calabar, Nigeria.</div></div></div>\n<p><b>The Nigeria gully erosion crisis</b> has been ongoing since before 1980, and affects communities large and small.  It is an <a href=\"/wiki/Ecological_crisis\" title=\"Ecological crisis\">ecological</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Environmental_disaster\" title=\"Environmental disaster\">environmental</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Economic_collapse\" title=\"Economic collapse\">economic</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Humanitarian_crisis\" title=\"Humanitarian crisis\">humanitarian</a> disaster resulting in <a href=\"/wiki/Land_degradation\" title=\"Land degradation\">land degradation</a>, loss of lives, and properties worth millions of dollars. The estimated number of <a href=\"/wiki/Gullies\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gullies\">gullies</a> in the country is at 3,000. Gullies and areas exposed to erosion in <a href=\"/wiki/Southeastern_Nigeria\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Southeastern Nigeria\">Southeastern Nigeria</a> tripled from about 1.33% (1,021 km<sup>2</sup>) in 1976 to about 3.7% (2,820 km<sup>2</sup>) in 2006 making the region the most affected region in the country.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Causes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Causes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Impact\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Impact</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Major_interverntions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Major interverntions</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Causes\">Causes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nigeria_gully_erosion_crisis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Causes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Gullies are majorly caused by <a href=\"/wiki/Surface_runoff\" title=\"Surface runoff\">surface runoff</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Erosion\" title=\"Erosion\">erosion</a> occurs, notably, in <a href=\"/wiki/Gully\" title=\"Gully\">gullies</a>, which grow wider and deeper with each rainfall.  Many of the gullies have become <a href=\"/wiki/Ravine\" title=\"Ravine\">ravines</a>, which can be dozens or hundreds of feet deep. Some natural processes can induce gullies, such as high amounts of rainfall, poor <a href=\"/wiki/Infiltration_(hydrology)\" title=\"Infiltration (hydrology)\">soil infiltration</a> and unfavorable <a href=\"/wiki/Drainage_basin\" title=\"Drainage basin\">catchment shape</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>However, in Nigeria, the causes of gully formation can be largely attributed to human activities such as:\n</p>\n<ul><li><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg/220px-Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"147\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg/330px-Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg/440px-Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"458\" data-file-height=\"307\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Poorly_terminated_drain.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Poorly terminated drain, a major cause of gully erosion</div></div></div>Poor <a href=\"/wiki/Highway_engineering\" title=\"Highway engineering\">road design</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Construction\" title=\"Construction\">construction</a> and abrupt termination of <a href=\"/wiki/Drainage\" title=\"Drainage\">drains</a>: When drains are not properly terminated, the flow in them usually with high <a href=\"/wiki/Pressure\" title=\"Pressure\">pressure</a> will disperse the earth below causing gullies rather than flow to lower catchment areas.</li>\n<li>Poor <a href=\"/wiki/Waste_management\" title=\"Waste management\">waste management</a> practices: Poor waste management practices such as dumping of <a href=\"/wiki/Waste\" title=\"Waste\">refuse</a> into drains and <a href=\"/wiki/Waterway\" title=\"Waterway\">waterways</a> prevent the proper flow of water. This practice results in <a href=\"/wiki/Flood\" title=\"Flood\">flooding</a> and if unchecked, it can lead to erosion of the top layer of the soil.</li>\n<li>Unsustainable <a href=\"/wiki/Land_use\" title=\"Land use\">land use</a> practices: Practices such as improper <a href=\"/wiki/Sand_mining\" title=\"Sand mining\">sand mining</a> strips away the top soil and tilling process associated with <a href=\"/wiki/Agriculture\" title=\"Agriculture\">crop cultivation</a> loosens the top soil, creating paths for runoff. <sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<p>Though concentrated in several towns and states in the Southeastern part of the country, the <a href=\"/wiki/Crisis\" title=\"Crisis\">crisis</a> affects all Nigerians indirectly. Homes and structures routinely collapse, as the gullies expand with each <a href=\"/wiki/Wet_season\" title=\"Wet season\">rainy season</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  Unchecked, the phenomenon will eventually transform the region into a <a href=\"/wiki/Badlands\" title=\"Badlands\">badland</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Impact\">Impact</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nigeria_gully_erosion_crisis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Impact\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Impacts caused by this environmental menace includes:\n</p>\n<ul><li>loss of <a href=\"/wiki/Infrastructure\" title=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</a> including roads, houses, and other real estate.</li>\n<li>loss of agricultural land and <a href=\"/wiki/Vegetation\" title=\"Vegetation\">vegetation</a>.</li>\n<li>Increased <a href=\"/wiki/Siltation\" title=\"Siltation\">siltation</a> in rivers leading to flooding.</li>\n<li>Increased <a href=\"/wiki/Sedimentation\" title=\"Sedimentation\">sedimentation</a> in waterways.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Major_interverntions\">Major interverntions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nigeria_gully_erosion_crisis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Major interverntions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In 2010, President Goodluck Ebele Jonathan made a request to the <a href=\"/wiki/World_Bank\" title=\"World Bank\">World Bank</a> Nigeria office for assistance in addressing the challenges of gully erosion, emerging Land degradation and environmental insecurity in the country. This request resulted in the formation of the <a href=\"/wiki/Nigeria_Erosion_and_Watershed_Management_Project\" title=\"Nigeria Erosion and Watershed Management Project\">Nigeria Erosion and Watershed Management Project</a> (NEWMAP), an eight (8) year multi-sectoral project aimed at addressing gully erosion in the Southern Nigeria and land degradation in the Northern Nigeria.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Before this intervention, several interventions failed to address the challenge of gully erosion mainly because of inefficiencies in designing proper structures and lack of commitment by the locals to take action.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>However, in some areas like Madona gully site, Awhum community Enugu State, and Okudu community Imo State, some sustainable interventions base on good practices were employed. These interventions addressed the menace of gully erosion in those areas.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nigeria_gully_erosion_crisis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Bank, The World (2012-04-12). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/728741468334143813/Nigeria-Erosion-and-Watershed-Management-Project\">\"Nigeria - Erosion and Watershed Management Project\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Nigeria+-+Erosion+and+Watershed+Management+Project&amp;rft.date=2012-04-12&amp;rft.aulast=Bank&amp;rft.aufirst=The+World&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdocuments.worldbank.org%2Fcurated%2Fen%2F728741468334143813%2FNigeria-Erosion-and-Watershed-Management-Project&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANigeria+gully+erosion+crisis\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">author. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/topics/land-and-soil/soil-degradation/gully-erosion\">\"Gully erosion\"</a>. <i>NSW Environment &amp; Heritage</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-02-05</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajour